## Obtaining source code {#obtaining-source-code}

1. Go to [https://github.com/Study-Scape/StudyScape](https://github.com/Study-Scape/StudyScape)  
2. Clone the repository by clicking on the green “Code” button  
3. Copy the web URL for cloning and use it to clone the repo in your IDE, however it is done.  
4. For access to the Supabase backend, please email one of our developers so they can add your email to the developer list.   
* Go to [https://supabase.com/](https://supabase.com/) to make an account and send to us the email you used to create the account if you haven’t done so already

## Building the software

1. Clone the repository: git clone [https://github.com/Study-Scape/StudyScape.git](https://github.com/Study-Scape/StudyScape.git)  
2. Install dependencies: npm install  
3. Set up environment variables: Locate provided .env.example file in study-scape directory  
4. Rename to .env.local  
5. Add the required API keys (message a StudyScape team member)  
6. Start the development server: npm run dev

## Testing the software![][image1]

We have automated tests through GitHub Actions\! Developers on any push commits and pull-requests will be automatically linted by Super-linter. On all pull-requests there will be: netlify checks for working deployment and deploy previews of features to the site, Our supabase database unit tests will all be run as well. Developers may also want to run these Actions locally before sending to remote and this can be done with [Act](https://github.com/nektos/act) (please refer to their user guide)\!

Our project only has a relevant database testing suite.

1. start docker  
2. run npx supabase start  
3. run supabase test db to test tables and columns  
4. run supabase stop to ensure stopping of the container

### Adding new tests

The only actual test files used are on the Supabase database; they are located in /StudyScape/study-scape/supabase/tests/database for pgTAP test.sql files. Any database sql tests should go in this folder, with the naming convention of test\_name.test.sql There are no tests for the frontend; we recommend having a discerning eye and ensuring that at least the use cases in the User Guide are operative before testing for a specific feature or bug. 

## Building a release

**How to build a release of the software.** Describe any tasks that are not automated. For example, should a developer update a version number (in code and documentation) prior to invoking the build system? Are there any sanity checks a developer should perform after building a release?

Our automated checks provide adequate sanity checks especially in having a working deployment to the site\! Every accepted pull-request and merge into main is ready for release. Developers can tag with the naming conventions of v(n+1).0.0 when finalizing a release\!
